# PowerShell Investigation

## Goal

Learn basic PowerShell navigation, file management, and how PowerShell can be used to investigate Windows systems.

## Skills Practiced

- PowerShell
- Windows Administration
- File Management
- Process Investigation
- Event Log Analysis
- Network Connections
- Command Line Navigation

## What I Learned

- How to navigate directories using PowerShell cmdlets.
- How to create, modify, and read files from the command line.
- How to view running processes, active network connections, and Windows Event Logs.
- The difference between relative and absolute file paths.
- That PowerShell supports Linux-style aliases (such as `ls`, `cd`, and `pwd`), although I intentionally used the full PowerShell cmdlets throughout this project.

## Project Files

- 4-PowerShell.pdf

## Reflection

PowerShell was different than I expected. I originally approached it like Linux, trying to learn navigation commands first, but quickly 
realized that PowerShell is much more useful as a way to ask Windows questions than simply move around the file system. One of the 
biggest lessons I learned was the importance of syntax, especially when working with file paths. Creating my own sandbox folder also made 
the project much easier to understand than working directly inside the System32 directory.

## More to Explore

- Learn basic PowerShell scripting.
- Filter Event Logs using PowerShell.
- Export command output to text files.
- Automate simple administrative tasks.
